{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488533"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:45:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:45:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"471"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/471"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.01,0.06,0.83,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103651"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/471"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86068"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7977"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36746"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103651"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a motor vehicle accident. He undergoes thoracoscopic examination and repair of a 6 cm defect in the apex of the right hemidiaphragm. A chest drain is inserted at the end of the procedure. Eight hours later, he develops tachypnoea and rapidly becomes short of breath. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 115/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. There are reduced breath sounds, reduced chest expansion, and hyper-resonance to percussion over the right lung field. There is good air entry on the left and the cardiac sounds are normal. There is no movement in the underwater seal drain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Air embolism","Pericardial tamponade","Haemothorax","Pneumothorax","Phrenic nerve injury"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has developed acute respiratory distress following thoracoscopic repair of a diaphragmatic injury. The clinical findings of reduced breath sounds, reduced chest expansion, and hyper-resonance to percussion on the affected side, combined with the absence of movement in the underwater seal drain, strongly suggest a \u003Cstrong\u003Epneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E. The chest drain has likely become blocked, allowing air to accumulate in the pleural space and causing lung collapse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAir embolism\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but serious complication that can occur during thoracic surgery when air enters the pulmonary veins or arteries. However, it typically presents with cardiovascular collapse, neurological symptoms, or both, rather than the respiratory findings described. Additionally, air embolism would typically occur during the procedure rather than eight hours later.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericardial tamponade\u003C/strong\u003E would present with hypotension, muffled heart sounds, and distended neck veins (Beck\u0027s triad), none of which are present in this case. Furthermore, tamponade would be more likely with a left-sided diaphragmatic injury due to proximity to the pericardium, whereas this patient had a right-sided repair. The timing of onset is also notably delayed for what one would expect to be an acute onset pericardial tamponade in the event of a crush injury to the chest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemothorax\u003C/strong\u003E would cause dullness rather than hyper-resonance to percussion. While a blocked chest drain could lead to accumulation of blood in the pleural space, the clinical findings of hyper-resonance make this diagnosis less likely. Additionally, significant haemothorax would typically cause hypotension, which is not present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhrenic nerve injury\u003C/strong\u003E could cause diaphragmatic paralysis, but this would not explain the acute onset of symptoms or the physical findings of hyper-resonance. The phrenic nerve runs along the medial aspect of the diaphragm near the vena cava, not at the apex where the repair was performed, making injury less likely during this procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of this patient would include immediate decompression of the pneumothorax, either by unblocking or replacing the chest drain, followed by ensuring adequate re-expansion of the lung. Chest X-ray would confirm the diagnosis and subsequent resolution after intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pneumothorax is a common complication after thoracic surgery, especially when chest drains become blocked.","Clinical signs of pneumothorax include reduced breath sounds, reduced chest expansion, and hyper-resonance to percussion on the affected side.","Blocked chest drains should be suspected when there is no movement in the underwater seal."],"references":["Solazzo, A., Barone, M., Bonanno, D., Sofia, C., Bottari, A., Ascenti, V., Familiari, D., Mazziotti, S., Cicero, G. and Monaco, F., 2021. Simultaneous pneumothorax and pneumoperitoneum as a late consequence of traumatic injury of the diaphragm: Multimodality imaging approach with surgical correlation and treatment. Radiology Case Reports, 16(9), pp.2421-2425."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86068"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"471"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86068"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T13:56:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T13:57:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"471"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103651"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"33","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/33"},"attributes":{"emoji":"